  "prompt": "In reaction, [math]N_2 O_4\\to {2NO_2}_{(g)}[/math], what will be the value of [math]K_C[/math] at 35\u00b0 C if [math]N_2 O_4[/math] is dissociated to the extent of 20% under a pressure of 1 atmosphere?",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step:\n\n1) First, write the balanced chemical equation:\n   [math]N_2 O_4 \\to 2 NO_2[/math]\n\n2) Set up an ICE table (Initial, Change, Equilibrium):\n   Let x be the volume fraction of [math]N_2 O_4[/math] that dissociates\n\n   \u2022 Initial: \n     [math]N_2 O_4 = 1[/math]\n     [math]NO_2 = 0[/math]\n\n   \u2022 Change: \n     [math]N_2 O_4 = -x[/math]\n     [math]NO_2 = +2x[/math]\n\n   \u2022 Equilibrium: \n     [math]N_2 O_4 = 1-x[/math]\n     [math]NO_2 = 2x[/math]\n\n3) Given: Dissociation is 20%, so x = 0.2\n\n4) Equilibrium concentrations:\n   \u2022 [math]N_2 O_4 = 1-0.2 = 0.8[/math]\n   \u2022 [math]NO_2 = 2(0.2) = 0.4[/math]\n\n5) Write the equilibrium constant expression:\n   [math]K_C = \\frac{[NO_2]^2}{[N_2 O_4]}[/math]\n\n6) Substitute values:\n   [math]K_C = \\frac{(0.4)^2}{0.8} = \\frac{0.16}{0.8} = 0.2[/math]\n\nTherefore, [math]K_C[/math] = 0.2 at 35\u00b0C.\n\nLet's verify the steps and calculations.\n\nKey steps:\n\u2022 Set up ICE table\n\u2022 Use fractional dissociation\n\u2022 Calculate concentrations\n\u2022 Use equilibrium constant formula\n\nThe answer is 0.2.",
